{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9a90adec-5a85-4f97-8fc6-62af7b4ce976","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect a trace (30s example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** in Visual Studio, PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (use `--format speedscope` for the latter).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use **dotnet-monitor** as a sidecar instead.\n- For production, prefer `--duration` over interactive stop to avoid forgetting and creating huge traces.\n- `dotnet-trace` uses EventPipe, so it's **low-overhead** and safe for production — no `ptrace` or elevated privileges needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ce02f837-a26b-42bc-86fb-16d4703f534c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise, practical advice.","outputTokens":390,"requestId":"D7C0:CE842:E3F472:106999B:69F2B029"},"id":"4e0e4f7d-16ea-4df9-95d7-2935e7c4fe53","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:28:19.686Z","parentId":"026b6699-fb5e-4b49-8a41-b48e0845b764"}
